06181nam a22008055i 9781487583422DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875834227 a10.3138/97814875834222doi  a(DE-B1597)545925  a(OCoLC)1149510543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a342.71/08522100aCharting the Consequences :bThe Impact of Charter Rights on Canadian Law and Politics /ced. by David Schneiderman, Kate Sutherland. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Impact (Real or Apprehended) of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms on the Legislative Authority of Quebec -- t2. Infertile Soil? Sowing the Charter in Alberta -- t3. Business, Economic Rights, and the Charter -- t4. The Impact of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms on Income Tax Law and Policy -- t5. Contemporary Traditional Equality: The Effect of the Charter on First Nations Politics -- t6. The Good, the Bad, and the Smugly: Sexual Orientation and Perspectives on the Charter -- t7. Rights, Nationalism, and Social Movements in Canadian Constitutional Politics -- t8. The New Equality Paradigm: The Impact of Charter Equality Principles on Private Law Decisions -- t9. The Charter and Access to Justice in Canada -- t10. The Charter and Mainstream Political Science: Waves of Practical Contestation and Changing Theoretical Currents -- tConclusion: Towards an Understanding of the Impact of the Charter of Rights on Canadian Law and Politics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1990, Supreme Court Justice Bertha Wilson proclaimed that the Canadian Charter of Rights 'is and must continue to be a vital force in molding the lives of Canadians.' In this collection of original essays commissioned by the Centre for Constitutional Studies, University of Alberta, legal and political scholars evaluate the impact of the Charter on life in Canada since 1982. Other works have focused on the jurisprudence of the Charter - its internal coherence or its implications for the role of courts. Charting the Consequences considers 'externalities' - the effect of the Charter and its jurisprudence on non-constitutional aspects of the law and on the dynamics of legislative power, provincial politics, and social movements. Specific contexts are examined, including certain provinces, economic rights, taxation, First Nations, sexual orientation, social movements, private law, access to justice, and political science. Patterns become manifest across contexts. For one, the editors identify three strata of actors in society - ranging from the powerful to the least powerful - who are affected by the Charter in differing degrees. Secondly, they expose how the actors' influences on Charter interpretation are determined, in some measure, by the magnitude of their social and political power. Charting the Consequences offers a fresh perspective on the Charter. It will generate new thinking and scholarship among lawyers, political scientists, and public policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil rightszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBakan, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Richard W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrows, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrowolsky, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Didi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id